article.description: Bobby Jackson scored a career-high 31 points and fueled a second-half run as the Sacramento Kings remained perfect at home with a 107-94 victory over the Los Angeles Clippers.
article.headline: Jackson's 31 lead Kings to eighth straight home win
article.linkText: Depleted Kings find enough bodies to beat Clippers
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Bobby Jackson thinks the Sacramento Kings have nearly perfected the concept of team play -- even when that team is two-thirds of its normal size.
Jackson

Jackson scored a career-high 31 points, and Doug Christie had a season-high 25 on Friday night as the injury-plagued Kings dressed only eight players and still remained perfect at home with a 107-94 victory over the Los Angeles Clippers. With Peja Stojakovic and Hedo Turkoglu joining three injured teammates in street clothes, Sacramento had the smallest roster allowed by NBA rules -- and somehow, it still wasn't a problem. Moving the ball with flair and running circles around the Clippers, the Kings cruised to a rout. "It's a test of our will right now, because it seems like this team has got a curse,'' Jackson said, only half-joking. "It's going to be tough, and we're going to be tired. We just have to play through it, because when we don't let things get to us, we play the best team basketball in the NBA.'' The Kings got impressive games from Jackson, who went 12-of-17 from the field and had eight rebounds, and Christie, who hit five 3-pointers. Chris Webber scored 16 points despite a serious case of the flu that forced him to the locker room twice during the game. Gerald Wallace added 13 points and 10 rebounds as the Kings improved to 8-0 at home -- their best start since moving to Sacramento -- and maintained their spot atop the Pacific Division with their seventh win in eight games. "I told the guys, 'I keep reading about how deep we are, so let's go out and find out,''' Kings coach Rick Adelman said. "I don't know what else could happen to us now. I don't care if we have seven, eight, nine guys: We're at Arco, and we should win. That's the attitude we have to have.'' Elton Brand had 25 points and 12 rebounds for Los Angeles, which had 12 healthy players but not much energy after a difficult overtime victory over New Jersey one night earlier. The Clippers shot poorly and gave up several big runs by the Kings -- and nobody could guard Jackson, who staked Sacramento to a big lead. "Bobby just really took over the game and made some big moves for that team,'' Brand said. "Until the third quarter, we were right in the game -- and then Bobby got going, and everything fell apart.'' Andre Miller, who had 37 points and 16 assists against the Nets, had 13 points and 11 assists. Marko Jaric added a career-high 19 points as Los Angeles lost for the fourth time in six games. Jackson has raised his game remarkably while starting in place of injured Mike Bibby this season. He was outstanding both inside and outside against the Clippers. He hit consecutive 3-pointers and a breakaway layup late in the third quarter to kick-start a 16-2 run that put the game away for Sacramento. "Bobby Jackson broke the game open,'' Clippers coach Alvin Gentry said. "He got an easy layup, but almost all the other shots were tough, with a hand in his face.'' With 11 minutes left, the sellout Arco Arena crowd began chanting "Bobby! Bobby!'' after the Kings announced a big push to get Jackson onto the Western Conference All-Star team as a reserve. "It's great to hear that, because I've been struggling,'' Jackson said. "There's no fans like Sacramento fans.'' Christie hit four 3-pointers in the first half, and the Kings led by 23 before the Clippers made a late run to respectability. Sacramento had just one eligible player on its bench at the end of the game: Webber was in the locker room, and Keon Clark fouled out with 2:01 left. "This one compliments our heart,'' Christie said. "We find ways to win, and that's hopefully what's going to push us over the top when the time comes in the playoffs.'' Stojakovic missed his fourth straight game with inflamed tissue in his right heel, and top reserve Turkoglu was out with a sprained right wrist. They joined Bibby, Mateen Cleaves and Scot Pollard on the Kings' already crowded bench, and they didn't sign any fresh bodies in time for Friday night's game. The Kings compensated for the absences with a simple solution: even more teamwork. Sacramento spent much of the night in a zone defense that conserved their players' energy, while Wallace and Christie stepped up their offensive efforts. Sacramento beat the Clippers for the 12th time in 16 meetings.

Game notes
Adelman won his 200th game with Sacramento. ... Tampa Bay Devil Rays slugger Greg Vaughn, a Sacramento native, was in his usual seat. ... With five minutes left, a fan screamed "Put in Terry Porter!'' The Kings' assistant coach, who retired last summer, grinned from his seat on the bench.
